(42, 9, 2, 58, 2, 3, 4, 'heal the sick', 'Connection of Healing and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing and the proclamation of salvation. Luke 9:2 mentions healing the sick, while Hebrews 2:4 refers to signs and wonders, which can include healing, confirming the message of salvation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 3, 42, 22, 35, 35, NULL, 'Provision in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of need when sent without provisions. This connection highlights the faithfulness of God in providing for His followers during their missions.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 3, 19, 37, 3, 3, NULL, 'Trust and Provision in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of reliance on God for provision. In both passages, there is an emphasis on trusting God to provide for needs during a journey or in daily life.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 3, 42, 10, 4, 12, 'Take nothing for your journey', 'Instructions for Mission', 'Both passages emphasize the directive to travel without provisions, highlighting reliance on hospitality and God''s provision. This connection underscores the theme of faith and dependence on others during their mission.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 3, 40, 10, 9, 14, 'Take nothing for your journey', 'Instructions for Missionary Travel', 'Both passages emphasize taking nothing for the journey, highlighting a shared directive to rely on hospitality and divine provision. This connection illustrates the theme of dependence on God and the community during their missions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 3, 55, 2, 4, 4, 'Take nothing for your journey', 'Focus on Spiritual Mission', 'This connection highlights the theme of prioritizing spiritual commitments over worldly concerns. Both passages emphasize the necessity of detachment from material possessions and distractions to fulfill one''s divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 3, 41, 6, 8, 11, 'Take nothing for your journey', 'Instructions for the Journey', 'Both passages emphasize taking nothing for the journey, highlighting a similar directive given to the disciples. This connection illustrates the shared theme of reliance on God during their mission.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 4, 40, 10, 11, 11, 'there abide', 'Abiding in a House', 'Both passages emphasize the instruction to ''abide'' in a location upon entering a new place. This connection highlights the importance of finding a suitable place to stay during their mission.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 4, 41, 6, 10, 10, 'there abide, and thence depart', 'Instructions for Entering Houses', 'Both passages emphasize the instruction to ''abide'' in a house until departing. This parallel highlights a consistent directive given to the disciples regarding their mission.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 4, 42, 10, 5, 8, 'there abide, and thence depart', 'Hospitality and Peace in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of hospitality and remaining in one place during ministry. The instruction to ''abide'' in a house connects to the directive to ''remain'' in the same house and eat what is provided, highlighting the theme of acceptance and peace in the context of sharing the message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 4, 44, 16, 15, 15, NULL, 'Hospitality and Abiding', 'Both passages emphasize the act of entering a house and abiding there. In Luke, Jesus instructs His disciples to stay in the house they enter, while in Acts, Lydia invites Paul and his companions to abide in her house after her baptism.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 5, 44, 13, 51, 51, 'shake off the very dust from your feet', 'Dust Shaking as Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust as a testimony against those who reject the message. This connection highlights a consistent response to rejection in the ministry of Jesus and the apostles.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 5, 44, 18, 6, 6, 'shake off the very dust from your feet', 'Rejection and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection and accountability in both passages. In Luke, the act of shaking off dust signifies a testimony against those who refuse to receive the message, while in Acts, shaking the raiment serves as a declaration of being free from responsibility for the rejected message.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 5, 40, 10, 14, 15, 'shake off the very dust from your feet', 'Dust Shaking as Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust as a testimony against those who reject the message. This connection highlights the seriousness of rejecting the disciples'' words and the consequences tied to such rejection.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 5, 41, 6, 11, 11, 'shake off the very dust from your feet', 'Dust Shaking as Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust as a testimony against those who do not receive the messengers. This connection highlights the seriousness of rejecting the message and the consequences tied to it.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 5, 42, 9, 48, 48, 'receive you', 'Receiving and Rejection Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of receiving and rejecting individuals in the context of Jesus'' ministry. Both passages emphasize the importance of reception, contrasting those who do not receive the disciples with those who receive a child in Jesus'' name.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 5, 42, 10, 10, 12, 'shake off the very dust from your feet', 'Dust Shaking as Testimony', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust as a testimony against those who reject the message. This connection highlights the seriousness of rejecting the kingdom of God and the consequences that follow. The phrase ''shake off the very dust from your feet'' in Luke 9:5 is echoed in Luke 10:10-12.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 5, 16, 5, 13, 13, 'shake off the very dust from your feet', 'Shaking Off Dust and Shaking Out', 'This connection highlights the act of shaking as a symbolic gesture of disassociation from those who do not uphold their commitments. Both passages emphasize the importance of accountability and the consequences of failing to receive or fulfill promises.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 6, 41, 6, 12, 13, 'preaching the gospel, and healing', 'Preaching and Healing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching and healing. They highlight the disciples'' mission to spread the gospel and perform healings, demonstrating a shared focus on ministry activities.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 6, 41, 16, 20, 20, NULL, 'Preaching and Healing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching the gospel ''every where'' and highlight the accompanying signs and healings. This connection illustrates a shared theme of the disciples'' mission and the divine support they received.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 6, 44, 4, 30, 30, 'healing every where', 'Healing and Signs Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing and the performance of signs and wonders. Luke 9:6 mentions healing everywhere, while Acts 4:30 speaks of healing through the name of Jesus, linking the ministry of the apostles to the works of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 6, 44, 5, 15, 15, 'healing every where', 'Healing Ministry Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing, with Luke highlighting the disciples'' preaching and healing, and Acts describing the healing power associated with Peter. This connection highlights the continuity of healing as a significant aspect of the early Christian ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 6, 42, 9, 1, 2, 'preaching the gospel, and healing', 'Connection of Preaching and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching and healing. In Luke 9:1-2, the disciples are sent to preach and heal, while Luke 9:6 describes their actions of preaching the gospel and healing everywhere.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 7, 40, 14, 1, 12, 'that John was risen from the dead', 'Herod''s Perplexity About John', 'Both passages emphasize Herod''s confusion regarding John the Baptist''s fate. In Luke, Herod is perplexed by the rumors of John''s resurrection, while in Matthew, he explicitly states that Jesus is John risen from the dead. This connection highlights Herod''s troubled conscience and the impact of John''s ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 7, 41, 6, 14, 28, 'that John was risen from the dead', 'Herod''s Perplexity about John', 'Both passages emphasize Herod''s belief that John the Baptist had risen from the dead, reflecting his confusion and guilt over John''s execution. This connection highlights Herod''s awareness of John''s significance and the miraculous works attributed to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 7, 42, 3, 1, 1, NULL, 'Herod''s Role in the Narrative', 'Both passages emphasize Herod''s position as tetrarch, linking him to significant events in Jesus'' ministry. Herod''s perplexity in Luke 9:7 reflects his ongoing involvement in the narrative established in Luke 3:1.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 7, 42, 9, 19, 19, 'that John was risen from the dead', 'Perceptions of Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection beliefs surrounding John the Baptist. Both passages reflect the confusion and speculation about John being risen from the dead or associated with other prophets.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 7, 18, 18, 11, 12, 'perplexed', 'Fear and Perplexity Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear and confusion present in both passages. Herod''s perplexity in Luke reflects the terror described in Job, as both characters face overwhelming circumstances that evoke fear.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 7, 19, 73, 19, 19, 'perplexed', 'Desolation and Perplexity Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of sudden fear and confusion. Herod''s perplexity about John''s resurrection parallels the terror described in Psalms, emphasizing the overwhelming nature of unexpected events.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 7, 23, 22, 5, 5, 'perplexed', 'Perplexity in Times of Trouble', 'This connection highlights the theme of perplexity present in both passages. In Luke, Herod''s confusion reflects a moment of trouble, while Isaiah describes a day of trouble and perplexity, indicating a shared experience of uncertainty.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
